<p class="BubbleTitleSection">LRPF Potential Contributions in the Changing Operating Environment</p>
<p>As adversaries continue to employ anti-access and area denial (A2/AD) capabilities to hinder or deny access to regions important to us, our allies and partners joint commanders responsible for neutralizing these capabilities in combat continue to cite their need for Army LRPF systems.  U.S. Forces Korea, USARPAC, ARCENT and USASOC have recognized the Army's unique LRPF attributes and potential future operational contributions in their respective areas of responsibility.   Because U.S. military strategy emphasizes the importance on A2/AD in the PACOM AOR the DoD is keenly interested in determining potential roles for Army rockets and missiles.</p>
<p>The potential for future Army LRPF roles in the PACOM A2/AD operating environment can be appreciated by understanding the many years of successful U.S. engagement and forward deployment of LRPF systems in forward presence and deterrence operations in Korea.  Long term U.S.–ROK engagement has involved LRPF roles in war games, experiments, multi-national science/technology initiatives and cooperative capabilities development.  One key result is that U.S. and Korean commanders have clear and mutually supporting responsibilities and common priorities for employment of LRPF systems.  Their LRPF missions include detailed deliberate and dynamic targeting of enemy air missile defenses and other A2/AD targets, long range high value targets, and time sensitive attack in support of offensive and defensive land forces maneuver and special operations forces.</p>
