			</div>
<p>LRPF has high potential as a future complementary joint fires capability in the expansive PACOM AOR.  It has unique attributes that will enable U.S. commanders to prevail with fires on and between large, dispersed land masses interspersed with sea lanes.  These attributes provide LRPF key advantages over other joint fires systems:  immediately available in significant quantities to U.S. and allied/partner commanders; permanent deterrence presence paired with small logistic footprint, mobility to respond to tactically dispersed operations; rapidly transportable within and between regions and theaters; responsiveness to requested fires; full functionality in all-weather conditions, high survivability and lethality against enemy A2/AD threats.  LRPF's contribution to operational and strategic level defenses in the ROK is an example of the successful achievement of Joint Operational Concept's imperative for delivering fires in depth.  Army LRPF systems demonstrate how joint fires can be forward positioned and adaptively employed to deter and respond to aggression against an ally / partner in what is always a unique A2/AD environment.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">Challenges to Army LRPF Capabilities</p>
<p>Sustainment of a robust Army LRPF capability is being adversely impacted by two factors.  First, as a result of a 2007 fiscally-based decision, the Army terminated the ATACMS program; inventories of both unitary and cluster munition warhead missiles are decreasing with time.  Second, the Department of Defense (DoD) Policy on Cluster Munitions bans the use of non-compliant systems after 31 Dec 2018; this will further decrease LRPF inventories.   DoD is pursuing studies to determine if, when, and the quantity of Army LRPF systems and alternate (area effects) warheads will be developed and fielded.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">LRPF Capabilities Development Modernization</p>
<p>The Army has two major LRPF modernization efforts underway to address long range fires gaps - the GMLRS Alternate Warhead (GMLRS-AW) and the ATACMS Service Life Extension Program (SLEP).  Other possibilities are being evaluated as complementary mitigating solutions as well.</p>
<p>The GMLRS-AW (Figure 4) will replace banned MLRS with current cluster munitions effective 31 Dec 2018.  GMLRS-AW provides a persistent capability to deliver area effects, similar to the munitions it replaces, to ranges greater than 70 Km.  Initial developmental testing flights have been successful.  The program is meeting all performance requirements and is on schedule to provide an initial operational capability 2016.</p>
