<p class="BubbleTitleSection">Science &amp; Technology</p>
<p>Combat developers at all levels collaborate with the Army Science &amp; Technology (S&amp;T) community to identify realm-of-the-possible LRPF solutions to address capability gaps.   Attributes being explored include an active radar guidance system, in-flight communications uplink to joint sensors, and maritime autonomous target recognition (ATR).  Improvements in technologies are contributing to the feasibility of longer range multi-use systems, such as new propellant and explosive energetics that enable reductions in weight, size and increased range. Analysis of possible system alternatives, combined with associated cost and performance attributes, will assist the LRPF combat developments community in determining courses of action to pursue.  USARPAC sees potential to collaborate with maritime forces in theater to develop ground-based anti-ship missiles for use in coastal defense and interdiction of warships.   The on-going OSD-directed LRPF Analysis of Alternatives will inform future senior Army and Office of Secretary of Defense leadership decisions on S&amp;T and program investments to address the Army's and Joint Force LRFP needs.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">Summary</p>
<p>The changing strategic, operational and threat environments demand modernization of current Army LRPF capabilities.  The aging ATACMS stockpile and loss of non-compliant CM missiles challenge DoD's ability to provide LRPF overmatch.  The Army and Fires warfighting function modernization proponent is addressing the challenges with an initial operating capability for GMLRS-AW in 2016, and ATACMS SLEP deliveries projected to start in 2018.   LRPF AoA results, projected for Mar 2015, will inform DoD leadership decisions on which DOTLMPF course of action to pursue.  A new missile solution could be ready in the 2022 timeframe in support of Joint, A2/AD and Army 2025 and beyond initiatives.</p>
